TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Implications of Competition Among Jurisdictions: Does Tiebout Need Politics?
AU  - Epple, Dennis
AU  - Zelenitz, Allan
Y1  - 1981/12/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261029
DO  - 10.1086/261029
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1197
EP  - 1217
VL  - 89
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The paper investigates whether compensation among local jurisdiction is, by itself, sufficient to ensure efficient provision of local public goods. Jurisdictions have fixed boundaries, and each has an entrenched government with the power to tax and supply the public good. Residents can move costlessly among jurisdictions. It is shown that competition among numerous jurisdictions is not sificient to guarantee public sector efficiency. Though residents can "vote with their feet," land is immobile. Hence, governments can unsurp some land rents for their own ends. Increasing the number of jurisdictions limits but cannot completely eliminate the ability to exercise discretionary governmental power.
AB  - The paper investigates whether compensation among local jurisdiction is, by itself, sufficient to ensure efficient provision of local public goods. Jurisdictions have fixed boundaries, and each has an entrenched government with the power to tax and supply the public good. Residents can move costlessly among jurisdictions. It is shown that competition among numerous jurisdictions is not sificient to guarantee public sector efficiency. Though residents can "vote with their feet," land is immobile. Hence, governments can unsurp some land rents for their own ends. Increasing the number of jurisdictions limits but cannot completely eliminate the ability to exercise discretionary governmental power.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261029
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261029
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Monetary Expansion and Real Exchange Rate Dynamics
AU  - Liviatan, Nissan
Y1  - 1981/12/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261030
DO  - 10.1086/261030
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1218
EP  - 1227
VL  - 89
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines the effect of a change in the rate of monetary expansion on the dynamics of the real exchange rate under fully flexible domestic prices and a floating exchange rate. The model is similar in structure to an ealier paper by Calvo and Rodríguez, the main difference being that in our model consumers have an infinite planning horizon and long-run perfect foresight. One of the main findings is that an increase in the rate of monetary expansion has the impact effect of creating a real appreciation of the exchange rate and a deterioration of the balance of payments, contrary to the results of Calvo and Rodríguez.
AB  - This paper examines the effect of a change in the rate of monetary expansion on the dynamics of the real exchange rate under fully flexible domestic prices and a floating exchange rate. The model is similar in structure to an ealier paper by Calvo and Rodríguez, the main difference being that in our model consumers have an infinite planning horizon and long-run perfect foresight. One of the main findings is that an increase in the rate of monetary expansion has the impact effect of creating a real appreciation of the exchange rate and a deterioration of the balance of payments, contrary to the results of Calvo and Rodríguez.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261030
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261030
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Economies of Scale and Barriers to Entry
AU  - Schmalensee, Richard
Y1  - 1981/12/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261031
DO  - 10.1086/261031
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1228
EP  - 1238
VL  - 89
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Dixit has recently presented a model in which established firms select capacity to discourage entry but cannot employ threats they would not rationally execute after entry. Entry deterrence in a slight modification of this model involves the classical limit-price output. Under linear or concave demand, however, the capital cost of a firm of minimum efficient scale is an upper bound on the present value of the monopoly profit stream that can be shielded from entry. It is argued that this suggests the general unimportance of entry barriers erected by scale economies.
AB  - Dixit has recently presented a model in which established firms select capacity to discourage entry but cannot employ threats they would not rationally execute after entry. Entry deterrence in a slight modification of this model involves the classical limit-price output. Under linear or concave demand, however, the capital cost of a firm of minimum efficient scale is an upper bound on the present value of the monopoly profit stream that can be shielded from entry. It is argued that this suggests the general unimportance of entry barriers erected by scale economies.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261031
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261031
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Great Depression and Commodity-exporting LDCs: The Case of Brazil
AU  - Cardoso, Eliana A.
Y1  - 1981/12/01
PY  - 1981
DA  - 1981/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261032
DO  - 10.1086/261032
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1239
EP  - 1250
VL  - 89
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper discusses the role of fiscal and monetary policies in an LDC with a major commodity export that is facing a depression abroad. The analysis is conducted in the context of a general equilibrium model which comprises a commodity-producing sector and an import-competing sector. Idle capacity and labor unemployment areassumed. Flexibility of the real exchange rate and industrial output responses to demand are the main adjustment mechanisms. The key to understanding the behavior of the Brazilian economy in 1930s is the government coffee-support policy which held the income of the export sector at a high level and hence enabled the manufacturing sector to expand. The fact that industrial output expanded in the face of both real depreciation and appreciation points to the importance of expenditure effects relative to price effects during the 1930s.
AB  - This paper discusses the role of fiscal and monetary policies in an LDC with a major commodity export that is facing a depression abroad. The analysis is conducted in the context of a general equilibrium model which comprises a commodity-producing sector and an import-competing sector. Idle capacity and labor unemployment areassumed. Flexibility of the real exchange rate and industrial output responses to demand are the main adjustment mechanisms. The key to understanding the behavior of the Brazilian economy in 1930s is the government coffee-support policy which held the income of the export sector at a high level and hence enabled the manufacturing sector to expand. The fact that industrial output expanded in the face of both real depreciation and appreciation points to the importance of expenditure effects relative to price effects during the 1930s.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261032
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261032
Y2  - 2024/03/22
